Now, we need to relate this to the supremum of the rest of the union.

The key insight is that `sSup (B N \ {a})` is less than or equal to `sSup ((⋃ N, ⋃ (hN : N ∈ D), B N hN) \ {a})`.

To see this, note that `B N \ {a}` is a subset of `(⋃ N, ⋃ (hN : N ∈ D), B N hN) \ {a}`.
